Pause checkpoint (post-demo prep): Maintenance Reporter roadmap
- Decision:
  - Pause active maintenance feature development until user demo and interest validation.
  - Keep current admin maintenance workflow unchanged during pause.

- Future direction (if resumed):
  - Build separate non-admin reporter interface for maintenance submission.
  - Preserve admin map as internal full-control workspace.

- Reporter experience goals:
  - Mobile-friendly, submit-focused map UI.
  - Tap/click location -> submit issue in simple 3-4 step flow.
  - Inputs: issue type, description, building, floor/room (if known), optional contact, optional photo.
  - Confirmation after submit.

- Reporter guardrails:
  - No edit/delete/assign/archive/export.
  - No admin-only metadata or internal notes.
  - Optional limited issue visibility to reduce duplicate reports (location/type/basic status only).

- Access and routing:
  - Suggested public reporter route: `/hastings/report`.
  - Support direct URL + QR code + facilities portal link.

- Data model and intake:
  - Save reporter submissions to same `maintenanceIssues` collection with source tag (`source = reporter/public`).
  - Default reporter status: `new`.
  - Include timestamp + submitted coordinates + optional location fields.
  - Reporter submissions appear in admin maintenance dashboard automatically.

- Security target:
  - Firestore rules allow reporter/public create.
  - Reporter/public read only limited approved fields (if public visibility is enabled).
  - Admin retains full CRUD.

- Nice-to-have backlog:
  - Auto-detect building from clicked polygon.
  - Photo upload path.
  - Duplicate warning for nearby existing issues.
  - Mobile geolocation centering.
  - QR code deployment workflow.

- Suggested implementation sequence:
  - Phase 1: reporter page + submit flow + Firebase write.
  - Phase 2: responsive/mobile UX hardening + optional limited issue visibility.
  - Phase 3: photo upload + QR workflow + validation/duplicate prevention.

Latest completed work (planner copilot phase 1 wiring)
- Added a selectable AI mode for `Create planning scenario`:
  - `Planner Copilot (multi-option)` and `Standard (single-pass)`.
- Added new backend endpoint:
  - `POST /create-move-scenario-copilot` in `ai-server/server.js`.
  - Generates multiple scored options (typically 3-5) with guardrails and fit scoring.
- Wired frontend create flow to call endpoint by selected mode:
  - Copilot mode sends `copilotOptionCount` and receives `copilot.generatedOptions`.
- Added copilot option switching in the results modal:
  - Shows option cards with SF/room/building counts.
  - `Use this option` swaps selected option and updates displayed candidates/totals.
- Fixed candidate post-processing bug:
  - Baseline-fill now runs against the effective selected option candidates (not only top-level defaults).
- Validation:
  - `npm.cmd run build` passed.
  - `npm.cmd run smoke` passed (`24/24 checks`).

Latest completed work (copilot type-fit-first fill logic + rationale upgrade)
- Improved planner copilot room fill behavior so it no longer optimizes mostly for SF closeness:
  - Fill pass now scores each candidate by net utility:
    - SF-gap improvement
    - Type-gap improvement (weighted higher)
    - single-building penalty (if enabled)
    - strong off-profile type penalty when room type is outside baseline mix
    - penalty when a pick worsens type fit
- Added stronger off-profile guardrail:
  - Large non-baseline room types are strongly discouraged as SF-only fillers.
  - Exception types can still be used as fallback, but with meaningful penalties.
- Upgraded per-room rationale text:
  - Uses type-aware reasons (for example, deficit reduction by SF) instead of mostly generic “Added to improve total SF fit.”
  - Explicitly labels SF-only fallback picks when type is outside baseline mix.
- Result:
  - Candidate tables should better reflect room-type fidelity and avoid obvious “big but wrong type” additions.
- Validation:
  - `node --check ai-server/server.js` passed.
  - `npm.cmd run build` passed.
  - `npm.cmd run smoke` passed (`24/24 checks`).

Latest completed work (floor summary fetch noise reduction)
- Reduced noisy floor-summary fetch errors for optional dashboard calculations:
  - `fetchFloorSummaryByUrl` now prefers local `campusRooms` in-memory rows (by building folder + floor) before attempting network GeoJSON fetch.
  - This avoids many unnecessary requests to floorplan files when equivalent room data is already loaded.
- Downgraded optional no-data floor summary logs from `console.warn` to `console.debug` in non-critical fallback paths.
- Result:
  - Fewer console warnings/errors during scenario + dashboard workflows.
  - Better resilience when GitHub Pages briefly returns 503 for specific floor assets.
- Validation:
  - `npm.cmd run build` passed.
  - `npm.cmd run smoke` passed (`24/24 checks`).

Latest completed work (copilot single-building guardrail tightening)
- Tightened Planner Copilot to better preserve single-building intent for department relocation:
  - Increased scoring penalty for building spread when single-building preference is active.
  - Reduced supplemental exception pooling in strict-fit mode:
    - Instead of pulling exception rooms from all buildings, copilot now chooses one best backup building and caps supplemental exception rooms.
- Strengthened frontend post-processing consistency:
  - Guardrail constraints (baseline fill + single-building constraint logic) are now applied to each copilot option before display.
  - Option cards now recalculate displayed totals/building count/displacement from constrained candidate sets, so UI reflects actual guarded options.
- Result:
  - Copilot options should no longer drift to 3-4 building spreads under the same single-building policy used by scenario selection.
- Validation:
  - `npm.cmd run build` passed.
  - `npm.cmd run smoke` passed (`24/24 checks`).

